# Cursor Rules for Whitespace Management

## Whitespace Rules

### Trailing Whitespace
- Remove trailing spaces and tabs from all lines
- No spaces or tabs should appear at the end of lines
- Empty lines should be truly empty (no whitespace characters)

### Whitespace-Only Lines
- Lines containing only spaces or tabs should be converted to empty lines
- Preserve intentional empty lines (no whitespace characters)
- Maintain code structure and formatting

### File Types

Apply these rules to all text files including:
- Shell scripts (.sh, .bash)
- Python files (.py)
- JavaScript/TypeScript (.js, .ts)
- HTML/CSS (.html, .css)
- Markdown (.md)
- Terraform (.tf)
- Configuration files (.yml, .yaml, .json, .xml)
- Documentation (.txt)
- Source code (.go, .rs, .java, .cpp, .c)

### Implementation
- When editing files, automatically remove trailing whitespace
- Convert whitespace-only lines to empty lines
- Show whitespace characters visually when editing
- Highlight trailing whitespace as an error
- Provide quick fix to remove trailing whitespace

### Exceptions
- Python files: Be careful with indentation (spaces are syntax)
- YAML files: Preserve meaningful whitespace structure
- Markdown files: Multiple spaces can create line breaks
- Assembly files: Some whitespace may be significant

### Visual Indicators
- Show trailing spaces as visible characters (·)
- Show tabs as visible characters (→)
- Highlight whitespace-only lines
- Use different colors for different types of whitespace issues

This rule ensures clean, consistent whitespace across all files while preserving the semantic meaning of whitespace where it matters.
